questionText: What seemingly ordinary moment in your life turned out to be a major turning point?

Because I have back issues, I had to use the stool from time to time. I knew it would likely hurt me, but I didn't it anyway. And hurt me, it did. I was unable to recover from the pain, and it was the final straw, so to speak, that then brought on a neurological disorder in full force.

questionText: If you were given the chance to relive any day in your life, do you know which day it would be? What happened?

I am a strong person now, and I am healing from my childhood traumas, some of them extreme. Were it not for so-called regrets, I may not have taken the time and energy to do deep-diving self-reflection. I like the new me, and every incident in my past has contributed to this peace about who I am.

questionText: Is there something about you that you struggle to admit to yourself or confront? Why?

The thing is not to repress all of it, but to examine it and find out why the shadow is there. It can be very sad and maybe a bit shameful to admit to yourself all these shortcomings, but they are there for a reason - usually from childhood trauma. It can also be from ancestral trauma or past life trauma. So the point of this life is to dive into yourself - know thyself - so that you can make peace with the parts of you that need healing. Then the shadows don't run your life, and you can be a well-balanced person.

questionText: Describe the weather where you are currently. Is this unusual weather for this time of year?

There's a pattern here where we go through lots of snow and extremely cold weather, then we have a reprieve of a couple winters that are nicer, and then we go back to the usual snowy, very cold winters. It's all cyclical, and we've come to accept that. That's how it is everywhere.

questionText: Do you think people can change fundamental things about who they are? If so, what kinds of things? If not, why not?

If we are talking about physical fundamentals - most of these things are changeable via plastic surgery/some other form of alteration, e.g. eye colour, body shape/size, weight, and so on.  In terms of personality, I think it is possible for people to change their perspectives and have their eyes opened as it were. Whether it is within the gift of everyone to change fundamental things about themselves I am less sure about. Sometimes close minded people become open minded because of external factors - e.g. a homophobic father might change his ways if he discovers his son is homosexual, a change that might not have otherwise happened.

questionText: Do you enjoy staying in hotels? What do you like or not like about them?
response: I do enjoying hotels, actually! There has only been 2 times when I got the feeling it wasn't a great idea (the worry of bed bugs and other domino-effect concerns..), out of around 10 times/10 hotels/motels in total. It was actually a moment to relax and not have to worry too much about things. It was a break from "life" as we know it, which is full of pressure's, stress, tension, un-ease! I like the fact that they usually contribute almost entirely to that "vacation" we mentally enter! What I do not like about them is sometimes there's things we see or hear, whether outside our room or entering/exiting, that may make the stay sketchy! Always the cheaper motels/hotels will have something that way (out of so many various things we will see, or sometimes hear..). One thing I did NOT like about them is that when I am in a hotel/motel, I do NOT want to be bothered at all! If I need sheets or towels, I will get them myself! Hard not to appreciate them knocking and checking, however the hotel/motel stays I have taken have ALWAYS been a mental break from life, in so many pretty crappy ways through my own life! Most recently, I have been thinking how great it would be to be able to book a hotel for a few weeks to just get away from our current 'crappy' situation... It is an escape, in my brain, that both my daughter and myself would enjoy right now.. The pro's to hotel stay's have certainly outweighed the cons!! Atleast in my own experience.

questionText: What seemingly ordinary moment in your life turned out to be a major turning point?
response: I will choose this current moment I am in, right now, in a place we moved in to 13 months ago.. I thought it was a new experience, one which I needed, to get moving forward in our lives, since we were away from a pretty troublesome environment. I figured that we had the normalcy necessary to live a normal life! It only took a single month to learn that not only was I wrong, but now I am going to carry a heavy burden, AGAIN, and am have to going to try to maintain myself as a model that my daughter needs, knowing damn well nothing at our hands for any relief will favor our situation that will actually omit the details that are flat out wrong from happening anymore! The major turning point is that what little faith I had in the system that is there for THIS has been almost entirely diminished, and I have practically no respect at all for it. It sometimes goes up, sometimes goes down, but ultimately, the turning point is that when, and if, you as a person happen to need help that requires another human being, and if your are not versed in social norms (or are just awkward or whatever...), you will continue to struggle until a burst of luck happens to come your way so that you can dig yourself out of a deep hole that only happened from you working VERY hard in various ways to do what you are supposed to do There's a few turning points here, actually, but the main one is how I am watching our criminal system favor someone taking advantage and that it happens to be the stronger weight, over my daughter being safe and feeling safe in HER home! So, someone who has done this through life repeatedly just doing it against us in our home again, versus the legal system not putting their foot down for a full year to get this house sane! Multiple turning points here, but my view of this system may be the biggest. I am going to try resolving this again today, so it is fresh in my mind after last night's noises.

questionText: What would your past self think of your current self? Would you say a lot has changed regarding how you think about the world and what you believe in?
response: A LOT has changed yes! My past self would never have believed, ever ever, that my capabilities would be so strained and so tested and so exhausted that I would ever need anything outside my own limits! My past self was super-man, do anything I set my mind too with enough dedication and efforts! Hard work NEVER came to my mind other than when I wondered why some people failed at their own goals. But currently, right now, self-neglect has taken a significant toll on me and my own life experiences have completely eliminated my faith in exterior sources already (a good example is injury attorneys-they are supposed to help and supposed to do what is right.....1 example of so many leading to this very day). My past self was aware of many things, but now that I am deep in the middle of it, witnessing this exact scenario, I now only believe that when someone sets their own deceptive goal, it will most likely outweigh the expectation that the 'right thing' will come in the end. I am still in the dust of these things so clarity has not yet come.

questionText: Do you think people can change fundamental things about who they are? If so, what kinds of things? If not, why not?
response: I feel that it is theoretically possible, but rarely happens in practice. This is because people are shaped by the society around them and tend to stay within the same or similar society through their lives. Of course there are physical things that people can't change, e.g. it is unlikely that the average person could make themselves into an Olympic athlete or a championship footballer. There are also probably limits to a person's intellectual ability especially if they had a poor education.

questionText: Do you think people can change fundamental things about who they are? If so, what kinds of things? If not, why not?

questionText: What do you value most in a friendship?
response: What I value most in a friendship is loyalty. I say this because I have experiences where people have said that they are my friend, but I have caught them telling lies about me or laughing about me behind my back to others. A lack of loyalty, in my opinion, can break a friendship. I like knowing that there is two-way mutual respect between us and that we will have each other's backs if someone said something rude or disparaging about the other. I like knowing that there is someone that I can count on. This makes it easier for me to form a connection and see the other person as someone that I can trust.
